The first part of the dataset, which requires interpretation, includes 4144 points. For each point, the 1D inversion set of functions from the pyGIMLi library (Rücker et al. 2017) is used in order to provide an interpretation of the sounding data. Note that the number of different resistivity layers of the soil ns\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
